07283nam a22010335i 9781846151576DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20032003xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97818461515767 a10.1515/97818461515762doi  a(DE-B1597)675239  a(OCoLC)1420506941  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aPN1995.9.M52 F55 2003eb 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a791.43658a809/.0200aStudies in Medievalism XII :bFilm and Fiction: Reviewing the Middle Ages /ced. by Martin Arnold, Tom Shippey.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2003] 1bD.S.Brewer, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (266 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Medievalism ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tDedication -- tEditorial Note -- tArthurian Melodrama, Chaucerian Spectacle, and the Waywardness of Cinematic Pastiche in First Knight and A Knight’s Tale -- tModern Mystics, Medieval Saints -- tSeeking the Human Image in The Advocate -- tHarold in Normandy: History and Romance -- tThe Day of a Thousand Years: Winchester’s 1901 Commemoration of Alfred the Great -- tEric Brighteyes: Rider Haggard Rewrites the Sagas -- t“Biddeth Peres Ploughman go to his Werk”: Appropriation of Piers Plowman in the Nineteenth and Twentieth Centuries -- tWhat Tales of a Wayside Inn Tells Us about Longfellow and about Chaucer -- tBad Baronets and the Curse of Medievalism -- t“The Bony, Grasping Hand”: Nineteenth-Century American Protestant Views on Medieval Canon Law -- tNotes on Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEssays on the continuing power and applicability of medieval images, with particular reference to recent films.The middle ages provide the material for mass-market films, for historical and fantasy fiction, for political propaganda and claims of legitimacy, and these in their turn exert a force well outside academia. The phenomenon is tooimportant to be left unscrutinised: these essays show the continuing power and applicability of medieval images - and also, it must be said, their dangerousness and often their falsity. Of the ten essays in this volume, several examine modern movies, including the highly-successful A Knight's Tale (Chaucer as a PR agent) and the much-derided First Knight (the Round Table fights the Gulf War). Others deal with the appropriation of history and literature by a variety of interested parties: King Alfred press-ganged for the Royal Navy and the burghers of Winchester in 1901, William Langland discovered as a prophet of future Socialism, Chaucer at once venerated and tidied into New England respectability. Vikings, Normans and Saxons are claimed as forebears and disowned as losers in works as complex as Rider Haggard's Eric Brighteyes, at once neo-saga and anti-saga. Victorian melodramaprovides the clichés of "the bad baronet" who revives the droit de seigneur (but baronets are notoriously modern creations); and of the "bony grasping hand" of the Catholic Church and its canon lawyers (an image spread in ways eerily reminiscent of the modern "urban legend" in its Internet forms). Contributors: BRUCE BRASINGTON, WILLIAM CALIN, CARL HAMMER, JONA HAMMER, PAUL HARDWICK, NICKOLAS HAYDOCK, GWENDOLYN MORGAN, JOANNE PARKER, CLARE A. SIMMONS, WILLIAM F. WOODS. Professor TOM SHIPPEY teaches in the Department of English at the University of St Louis; Dr MARTIN ARNOLD teaches at University College, Scarborough.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivilization, Medieval, in literature. 0aLiterature, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, ModernxHistory and criticism. 0aMedievalism in literature. 0aMiddle Ages in literature. 0aMiddle Ages in motion pictures. 4aFilm & Theatre. 4aMedieva